at|Although the Clubs have started well, you have a losing club which needs to be discarded.   The only reasonable chance for that is to find the  @dA  onside.   There is very little chance of finding West with 5 @d's (and East with @dAxx), which would allow you to ruff out the Ace.  
^^There is similarly no chance of the @c98  disappearing into thin air.|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


---------------------------------------------------------------------------
qx|Ans,wide|
nt|^z@3^b@2^^|n^|5|
lg|f|
at|So your plan should be a very simple one, a @h to dummy's Ace and a @h back to the King in hand (however the trumps are distributed - in practice East had both of them) and then lead the @d towards the King.  West, holding the @dAce, is powerless.  They either let the @dK win, in which case your 3rd losing trick disappears, or they rise with the @dA and now the @dK takes care of your 3rd @c.|
n#|7|at|^^If it turns out that East has the @dAce, you've lost nothing, because the hand was unmakeable.|
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


